Solution 4: We could have chosen a different kind of Riemann sum.


 We didn't have to assume that we were dealing with a right Riemann sum. Suppose \Delta x =2, and we have a midpoint Riemann sum.


 Let's match up what we're given in the problem with what we're given in the definition:


\Delta x \cdot f\left(a+\left(i-\tfrac{1}{2}\right)\Delta x\right)&=2\cdot\left(5+2i\right)^2

2 \cdot f\left(a+\left(i-\tfrac{1}{2}\right)2\right)&=2\cdot\left(5+2i\right)^2

f\left(a+\left(i-\tfrac{1}{2}\right)2\right)&=\left(5+2i\right)^2

f\left(a+2i-1\right)&=\left(5+2i\right)^2

f\left((a-1)+2i\right)&=\left(5+2i\right)^2




 It is now convenient to set a-1=5, hence a=6.


 Then f(\textcolor{red}{5+2i})=(\textcolor{red}{5+2i})^2, so f(\textcolor{red}{x})=\textcolor{red}{x}^2


 Since 2=\frac{b-a}{3} and a=6, we see b=12.





